The bug is that if you input two strings that are the same, then the function returns the length of the string as the length of the LCS.

## Fix

To fix this, we can use a flag to indicate if the strings are the same, and use the length of the LCS as the length of the string when the strings are the same.

```
def longest_common_subsequence_length(str1, str2):
    m = len(str1)
    n = len(str2)

    if str1 == str2:
        return 0

    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]

    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if str1[i - 1] == str2[j - 1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1])

    return dp[m][n]
```

